Failed to orbit; carrier rocket exploded due to excessive vibration.[3][5]

Failed to orbit; premature second-stage cutoff due to erroneous command by

Failed to orbit; seal failure in hydrogen peroxide pump cooling system

Failed to orbit; premature first-stage cutoff.[3] Reached apogee of 102,360

Failed to orbit; guidance system malfunction.[9]

Failed to orbit; premature third-stage cutoff.[15]
Failed to orbit; rocket disintegrated ten seconds after launch.[15]

Failed to orbit; second-stage oxidizer system malfunction resulting in

Failed to orbit, exploded 68 seconds after launch, at an altitude of 12.2

Partial launch failure due to guidance problem; attempt to correct using

Failed to deploy solar panels, ran out of power ten hours after launch;

The impact made the United States the 2nd country to reach the surface of

Failed to depart Low Earth orbit;[22] guidance system power failure

Failed to perform mid-course correction,[23] remained in high Earth orbit

Failed to orbit; third stage underperformed due to oxidiser valve failure.

Failed to orbit; power failure caused by broken connection resulted in

Failed to depart low Earth orbit.[30]

Third stage failed to ignite due to loss of oxidiser pressure, failed to

Loss of control after gyroscope malfunction,[28] failed to decelerate for

Engine failed to shut down after performing mid-course correction manoeuvre,
[28] flew past the Moon in a heliocentric orbit.[33]

Flew past the Moon on 20 July 1965 at a distance of 9,200 kilometres

Attitude control failure shortly before landing prevented controlled

Landing airbag punctured, resulting in loss of attitude control shortly

*First spacecraft to land successfully on the Moon*. Touchdown on 3

Upper stage lost attitude control and failed to ignite;[38] spacecraft

Entered orbit at 18:44 UTC on 3 April 1966, becoming the *first spacecraft

Landed in Oceanus Procellarum on 2 June 1966 at 06:17:36 UTC.[38] Returned

Magnetospheric probe; rocket imparted greater velocity than had been 
planned, leaving spacecraft unable to enter orbit.[38] Repurposed for Earth

Orbital insertion at around 15:36 UTC on 14 August. Deorbited early due to

Entered orbit on 28 August 1966. Failed to return images; other instruments 
operated correctly.[38] Conducted gamma ray and X-ray observations to study

Ceased operation on 1 October 1966 after power was depleted.[44]

One thruster failed to ignite during mid-course correction manoeuvre, 
resulting in loss of control.[38] Impacted the Moon at 03:18 UTC on 23 
September 1966.[45]

Entered orbit on 25 October 1966 and returned data until 19 January 1967.
[46] Completed photography mission intended for Luna 11.[38]

Entered orbit at about 19:51 UTC on 10 November 1966 to begin photographic 
mapping mission. Impacted on the far side of the lunar surface following

Successfully landed in Oceanus Procellarum at 18:01 UTC on 24 December 1966.
[38] Returned images from the surface and studied the lunar soil.[48] 
Operated until depletion of power at 06:31 UTC on 28 December.[38]

Entered orbit at 21:54 UTC on 8 February 1967. Deorbited at end of mission 
and impacted the Moon on 9 October 1967.[49]

Landed at 00:04 UTC on 20 April 1967 and operated until 3 May.[50][51] 
Visited by Apollo 12 astronauts in 1969, with some parts removed for return

Entered orbit at 21:54 UTC on 8 May 1967, operated until 17 July. Decayed

Contact with spacecraft lost at 02:03 UTC on 17 July, two and a half 
minutes before scheduled landing.[50] NASA determined that the spacecraft

Magnetospheric probe, studying the Moon and interplanetary space. 
Deactivated on 27 June 1973.[55] Presumed to have impacted the Moon during 
the 1970s.[56]

Final mission in the Lunar Orbiter series, entered selenocentric orbit on 5 
August at 16:48 UTC and conducted a photographic survey until 18 August. 
Deorbited and impacted the Moon on 31 January 1968.[57]

Landed in *Mare Tranquillitatis* at 00:46:44 UTC on 11 September. Last

Technology demonstration for planned crewed missions. Failed to reach orbit 
after a blocked propellant line caused one of the first-stage engines to 
not ignite.[50]

Landed in *Sinus Medii* at 01:01:04 UTC on 10 November.[50] Made brief

on 14 December.[59]

Technology demonstration for planned crewed missions; unable to achieve 
orbit after second-stage engine failed to ignite.[50]

Final Surveyor mission.[60] Landed 29 kilometres (18 mi) from *Tycho* 
crater at 01:05:36 UTC on 10 January. Operated until 21 February 1968.[61]
Failed to orbit after third stage ran out of fuel.[61]

Tested communications for proposed crewed missions and studied the mass 
concentration of the Moon. Entered orbit on 10 April at 19:25 UTC.[62]

Technology demonstration for planned crewed missions. Failed to orbit after 
second-stage engine incorrectly commanded to shut down. Spacecraft was 
recovered using its prototype launch escape system.[61]

Two tortoises and other life forms on board a technology demonstration for 
planned crewed missions. Made a closest approach of 1,950 kilometres 
(1,210 mi) on 18 September, and circled the Moon before returning to Earth. 
Landed in the Indian Ocean on 21 September at 16:08 UTC, becoming the *first 
Lunar spacecraft to be recovered successfully* and carried the *first Earth 
life to travel to and around the Moon*.[63]

Technology demonstration for planned crewed missions. Carrying turtles in 
the second mission of earthlings[*clarification needed*] to close proximity 
of the Moon, the flyby was on 14 November, with a closest approach of 2,420 
kilometres (1,500 mi).[64]

Reentered Earth's atmosphere on 17 November; however, recovery was 
unsuccessful after parachutes were prematurely jettisoned.[61]

*First crewed mission to the Moon*; entered orbit around the Moon with 
four-minute burn beginning at 09:59:52 UTC on 24 December. Completed ten 
orbits of the Moon before returning to Earth with an engine burn at 
06:10:16 UTC on 25 December. Landed in the Pacific Ocean at 15:51 UTC on 27 
December.[65]

Technology demonstration for planned crewed missions. Failed to orbit after 
one of the four second-stage engines shut down prematurely. Third-stage 
engine also shut down prematurely. The spacecraft was recovered using its 
launch escape system.[66]

First launch of the Lunokhod rover. Launch vehicle disintegrated 51 seconds 
after launch and exploded.[67]

First launch of N1 rocket; intended to orbit the Moon and return to Earth. 
First stage prematurely shut down 70 seconds after launch; launch vehicle 
crashed 50 kilometres (31 mi) from launch site. Spacecraft landed some 35 
kilometres (22 mi) from the launch pad after successfully using its launch 
escape system.[67]

Dress rehearsal for Apollo 11. Lunar Module with two astronauts on board 
descended to a distance of 14.326 kilometres (8.902 mi) above the lunar 
surface.[68]

Intended to land on the Moon and return lunar soil sample. Did not reach 
Earth orbit after fourth stage failed to ignite.[66]

Intended to orbit the Moon and return to Earth. All first-stage engines 
shut down 10 seconds after launch; launch vehicle crashed and exploded on 
the launch pad. Spacecraft landed safely 2 kilometres (1.2 mi) from the 
launch site after using launch escape sequence.[67]

Reached lunar orbit at 10:00 UTC on 17 July. Descent retro-rocket burn 
started at 15:47 UTC on 21 July. Contact lost three minutes after de-orbit 
burn; probably crashed on the Moon.[67]

*First crewed landing on the Moon.* The Lunar Module *Eagle* landed at 
20:17 UTC on 20 July 1969.

Technology demonstration for planned crewed missions. Carried four turtles 
in a lunar flyby on 10 August, with a closest approach of 1,200 kilometres

Third attempt at lunar sample return. After reaching low Earth orbit, the 
fourth-stage engine failed to fire for trans-lunar injection due to 
oxidiser leak. Spacecraft re-entered Earth's atmosphere about 4 days after 
launch.[67]

Fourth attempt at lunar sample return. After reaching low Earth orbit, the 
fourth-stage engine failed to fire for trans-lunar injection due to control 
system malfunction. Spacecraft re-entered Earth's atmosphere within one 
orbit after launch.[67]

Lunar landing aborted following Service Module oxygen tank explosion en 
route to the Moon; flew past the Moon (free-return trajectory) and returned 
the crew safely to Earth.

Technology demonstration for planned crewed missions; returned to Earth 
successfully.
Fourth crewed lunar landing, and first to use the Lunar Roving Vehicle.
Failed during descent to lunar surface.

Entered an orbit around the Moon on 2 October 1971 after two midcourse

*Luna 20* soft landed on the Moon in a mountainous area known as the Terra

Failed to orbit; intended to orbit the Moon and return to Earth.

Sixth and last crewed lunar landing and last use of the Lunar Roving Vehicle;

Radio astronomy spacecraft, operated in selenocentric orbit to avoid 
interference from terrestrial radio sources.
Interplanetary spacecraft, mapped lunar north pole to test cameras.
Inserted into a circular lunar orbit on 2 June 1974

Tipped over upon landing, precluding any sample return attempt. Functioned

Series of flybys to regulate high Earth orbit.

Two flybys en route to Mars.
Flyby on 30 July 2001 to reach the Earth‚ÄìSun L2 Lagrangian point.

Both component spacecraft entered heliocentric orbit on 15 December 2006.

Two THEMIS spacecraft moved to selenocentric orbit for extended mission;

Deployed *Okina* and *Ouna* satellites. *Kaguya* and *Okina* impacted the

Impacted Moon in USGS quadrangle LQ21 on 1 March 2009, at end of mission.

Succeeded through mission. Orbit lasted 312 days, short of intended 2

[74] Moon Impact Probe was deployed from the orbiter. It successfully

Observed impact of Centaur upper stage that launched it and LRO, then

Following completion of six month Lunar mission, departed selenocentric

Impacted the Moon in USGS quadrangle LQ01 on 17 December 2012 at end of

Mission ended on 18 April 2014, when the spacecraft's controllers

Entered orbit on 6 December 2013 with landing at 13:12 UTC on 14 December.

Demonstration of re-entry capsule for Chang'e 5 sample-return mission at

Uncrewed test of Orion spacecraft in lunar flyby and lunar Distant

H-Map will search for evidence of lunar water ice inside permanently

It is designed to image the Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage and will

It is to flyby the Moon and collect its surface thermography.
It is a solar sail that will flyby a near-Earth asteroid.

It will image the Earth's plasmasphere, impact craters on the Moon's far

It was a lunar surface probe attempting to semi-hard land using solid

CubeSat spacecraft on an astrobiology mission that will use budding yeast

CubeSat to orbit the Sun to study the dynamic particles and magnetic fields.

CubeSat that will demonstrate navigation in deep space using innovative plasma

Lunar lander technology demonstration.[94] Contact lost during final stage

Lunar rover demonstration. Launched aboard ispace's Hakuto-R lander.[96]

Initially scheduled to be launched on the Artemis 1 mission, moved to a Falcon

Will fly by the Moon in August 2024 en route to Ganymede.

Launched on 14 July 2023, Orbit insertion on 5 August 2023, Lander

Launched on 10 August 2023, Orbital insertion on 16 August 2023, failed
